1 Flexdashboard

  1. We can setup the layout:
  • vertical_layout: fill/scroll
  • orientation: column/rows
  • to make the panel 1 column/row, we can add ### in new line
  1. Template:
  • Input your code of importing data until data preparation before the chunk of Rows/Columns
  • We dont need to print the data if we dont want to show the data in our dashboard
  • Input your code of making some plot and print the plot in the chunk after Rows/Columns
  1. Consideration:
  • Advantage: theres template to make it easier
  • Disanvantage: user cant giving some input
  1. Reference:

2 Shiny

Shiny is an open package from RStudio, which provides a web application framework to create interactive web applications (visualization) called Shiny apps. The ease of working with Shiny has what popularized it among R users. These web applications seamlessly display R objects (like plots, tables etc.) and can also be made live to allow access to anyone.

Shiny provides automatic reactive binding between inputs and outputs. It also provides extensive pre-built widgets which make it possible to build elegant and powerful applications with minimal effort.

Structure of a basic shiny apps:

  • global.R: For setting-up the apps environment, e.g., libraries, import and initial cleaning dataset
  • ui.R: User Interface (UI) for displaying input and output
  • server.R: For processing users input and render it into output

One of many useful libraries that we can use is shinydashboard. We can use shinydashboard to create a dashboard apps for our users.

2.1 Basic UI Parts

The most common way is to add sidebarMenu() on the sidebar side and tabItems() on the body side:

  • global.R:
# library setup
library(shiny)
library(shinydashboard)
library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
library(readr)
library(DT)
library(dplyr)
library(scales)
library(glue)
library(tidyverse)
options(scipen = 99)
  • ui.R:

Notice that weve added sidebarMenu() on dashboardSidebar(), and tabItems() on dashboardBody()

header <- dashboardHeader()
sidebar <- dashboardSidebar()
body <- dashboardBody()

dashboardPage(header = header, sidebar = sidebar, body = body)
  • server.R:
function(input, output) {

}

2.3 Set-up your First Input-Output Flow

A very common input-output flow can be outlined into some parts:

  • input: use *Input() in ui.R, e.g.selectInput()
  • render: use output$outputName <- render*({ return(output_object) }) in server.R
  • output: use *Output("outputName")in ui.R

In the real usage, you can change * with some basic grammar we frequently use.

For example:

  • input: selectInput() for providing select input to users
  • render: output$outputID <- renderPlot({}) for rendering a static plot output or output$outputID <- renderPlotly({}) for rendering a dinamic plot output
  • output: plotOutput("outputID") for displaying a static plot output or plotlyOutput("outputID") for displaying a dinamic plot output

Lets simulate each part step-by-step to work on our Women Workers Shiny!

2.3.1 1. Defining Input

  • global.R

Call all libraries and read data in global.R. Notice that we also create selectYear, which will be the options that appear on our selectInput():

# library setup
library(shinydashboard)
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
library(shiny)
library(glue)
library(scales)
library(DT)

# import data
avo <- read_csv("../data_input/avocado.csv")

# data preparation
avo <- avo %>% 
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)

#theme algoritma
theme_algoritma <- readRDS("../theme_algoritma.rds")
  • ui.R

Notice that we now also add fluidRow() and column() to define the body layout of Dashboard tab and Table tab. Then, we add selectInput there.

header <- dashboardHeader(title = "Avocado Price Dashboard")

sidebar <- dashboardSidebar(
    sidebarMenu(
        menuItem(text = "Dashboard", tabName = "dashboard", icon = icon("dashboard")),
        menuItem(text = "Region Price", tabName = "chart", icon = icon("chart-line")),
        menuItem(text = "Dataset", tabName = "data", icon = icon("table"))
    )
)
body <- dashboardBody(
    tabItems(
        tabItem(tabName = "dashboard",
                fluidRow(column(width = 12,
                                plotlyOutput(outputId = "plot1"))),
                br(),
                br(),
                # fluidRow(box()),
                fluidRow(column(width = 12,
                                plotlyOutput(outputId = "plot2"))
                         )
                ),
        tabItem(tabName = "chart",
                fluidRow(box(width = 3,
                             title = "Avocado type", status = "primary",
                             radioButtons(inputId = "type",
                                          label = "Select avocado type",
                                          choices = levels(avo$type)
                                          )
                             ),
                         column(width = 9,
                                plotlyOutput(outputId = "plot3"))
                         ),
                fluidRow(column(width = 12,
                                selectInput(inputId = "region",
                                            label = "Select the Region",
                                            choices = levels(avo$region)),
                                plotlyOutput(outputId = "plot4")))
                ),
        tabItem(tabName = "data",
                fluidRow(column(width = 12,
                                dataTableOutput(outputId = "data_avo"))))
    )
)


dashboardPage(header = header, sidebar = sidebar, body = body)
  • server.R
function(input, output){
    output$plot1 <- renderPlotly({
        p1 <- avo %>% 
            ggplot(aes(x = AveragePrice)) +
            geom_histogram()+
            labs(title = "Distribusi Harga Alpukat", x = NULL, y = NULL) +
            scale_x_continuous(label = unit_format(prefix = "$ ", unit = "")) +
            theme_algoritma
        
        ggplotly(p1, tooltip = "x")
    })
    
    output$plot2 <- renderPlotly({
        
        p2 <- avo %>% 
            filter(AveragePrice >= 1 & AveragePrice <= 1.5) %>% 
            ggplot(aes(x = type, y = AveragePrice)) +
            geom_boxplot(aes(fill = type)) +
            labs(title = "Distribusi Harga Alpukat", subtitle = "pada Tipe") +
            theme_algoritma +
            theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12))
        
        ggplotly(p2)
        
    })
    
    output$plot3 <- renderPlotly({
        type_avo <- input$type
        
        # aggregasi
        min_price <- avo %>% 
            filter(AveragePrice >= 0.95 & AveragePrice <= 1.6) %>% 
            filter(type == type_avo) %>% 
            group_by(region) %>% 
            summarise(mean_price = mean(AveragePrice)) %>% 
            ungroup() %>% 
            arrange(mean_price) %>% 
            head(10)
        
        # visualiasasi
        p3 <- min_price %>% 
            ggplot(aes(y = reorder(region, desc(mean_price)), x = mean_price, 
                       label = round(mean_price,2))) +
            geom_col(aes(fill = mean_price), show.legend = F) +
            geom_text(nudge_x = 0.1) +
            scale_fill_gradient(high = "#132B43", low = "#56B1F7") +
            ggtitle(label = paste("10 Region has Lowest", type_avo, "Avocado Price")) +
            labs(x = NULL, y = NULL) +
            theme_algoritma
        
        ggplotly(p3)
    })
    
    output$plot4 <- renderPlotly({
        
        type_avo <- input$type
        region_data <- input$region
        
        data <- avo %>% 
            filter(type == type_avo) %>% 
            filter(region == region_data)
        
       p4 <- data %>% 
            ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = AveragePrice)) +
            geom_line(aes(group = region_data, col = region_data)) +
            geom_point(size = 0.01) +
            theme_algoritma
       
       ggplotly(p4)
       
    })
    
    output$data_avo <- renderDataTable({
        datatable(data = avo, options = list(scrollX =T, scrollY = T))
    })
        
}

  • server.R:

Were now doing the rendering process on the server side

function(input, output) { 
    gap_worker <- reactive({
        
        year_option <- input$gap_workers
        
        gap <- workers %>% 
            filter(year == year_option) %>% 
            group_by(major_category) %>% 
            summarise(Male = round(mean(workers_male/total_workers)*100,2),
                      Female = round(mean(percent_female),2)) %>% 
            ungroup() %>% 
            gather(key = "gender", value = "mean_workers", Male, Female)
        
        return(gap)
    })
    
    output$plot1 <- renderPlotly({
        data_input <- gap_worker()
        
        year_option <- input$gap_workers
        
        p1 <- ggplot(data_input, aes(x = major_category, y = mean_workers, 
                                     text = paste(gender, ":", mean_workers))) +
            geom_col(position = "stack", aes(fill = gender))+
            coord_flip()+
            labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, title = paste("Men vs Female Workers in", year_option)) +
            theme_algoritma +
            theme(legend.position = "none")+
            scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkred", "grey0"))
        
        ggplotly(p1, tooltip = "text")
    })
    
}

2.3.3 3. Displaying Output

2.3.4 4. To add other elements (input/render/output), repeat above steps iteratively!

In this steps, we want to customize giving box in plot and the text in the box. You can use h5() if size of text is like heading 5. Or if you want the text size bigger than that, you can use h4. The bigger the number so the text size will be smaller.

  • global.R
